hands_on_practices.problem:
A pair of diastereotopic protons in an organic molecule exhibits an AB-type Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) spin system at high field. The spins are coupled by an isotropic scalar coupling and have different Larmor frequencies relative to the carrier, producing an AB quartet. The canonical two-spin-1/2 isotropic Hamiltonian in frequency units is given by
$$
 rac{H}{h} \;=\; 
u_{A} I_{Az} \;+\; 
u_{B} I_{Bz} \;+\; J \left( I_{Ax} I_{Bx} \;+\; I_{Ay} I_{By} \;+\; I_{Az} I_{Bz} ight),
$$
where $h$ is Planck’s constant, $
u_{A}$ and $
u_{B}$ are the Larmor frequencies in $\mathrm{Hz}$ of spins $A$ and $B$, $J$ is the scalar coupling in $\mathrm{Hz}$, and $I_{A\alpha}$ and $I_{B\alpha}$ for $\alpha \in \{x,y,z\}$ are spin operators. Define the frequency difference by $\Delta \equiv 
u_{A} - 
u_{B}$ and the mean frequency by $ ar{
u} \equiv (
u_{A} + 
u_{B})/2$.

In the AB spectrum, the four transitions appear symmetrically about $ ar{
u}$. Let $p$ denote twice the offset (in $\mathrm{Hz}$) from $ ar{
u}$ to the outer lines on either side, and let $q$ denote twice the offset (in $\mathrm{Hz}$) from $ ar{
u}$ to the inner lines on either side. Thus the outer lines are at $ ar{
u} \pm p/2$ and the inner lines are at $ ar{
u} \pm q/2$, with $p > q > 0$ measured directly from the spectrum.

Starting from the Hamiltonian above and fundamental spin-operator algebra, derive the four energy eigenvalues, identify the four allowed single-quantum transitions, and show that $p$ and $q$ satisfy two invariants that allow determination of the scalar coupling $J$ and the magnitude of the frequency difference $|\Delta|$. Explain carefully why only $|\Delta|$ is accessible from line positions, not the sign of $\Delta$.

For a particular AB spectrum recorded at a spectrometer frequency of $500\,\mathrm{MHz}$, the measured values are $p = 80.0\,\mathrm{Hz}$ and $q = 20.0\,\mathrm{Hz}$. Using your derived invariants, compute $J$ and $|\Delta|$. Express your final numerical answers in $\mathrm{Hz}$ and round to four significant figures.
